Difference between Http request and Http session

HTTP Request:

Definition:
A single call from a client (browser, app, etc.) to the server, such as loading a page or
submitting a form.

Scope:
Lasts only as long as the server is processing that one request.

Spring Scope:
Beans with @Scope("request") are created new for each HTTP request.

Example Use:
Tracking data for a single page load or form submission.

HTTP Session:

Definition:
A series of requests from the same user/client, grouped together by the server to maintain
state (like login status) across multiple requests.

Scope:
Lasts as long as the user is interacting with the application (until they log out or the
session times out).

Spring Scope:
Beans with @Scope("session") are created once per user session and shared across all requests
in that session.

Example Use:
Storing user login information, shopping cart contents, or preferences.


Summary Table:

Feature	                 HTTP Request	                      HTTP Session

Lifetime	             One client-server interaction	Multiple interactions (user session)
Scope	                 Short (milliseconds/seconds)	Longer (minutes/hours)
Spring Scope	         @Scope("request")	            @Scope("session")
Use Case	             Per-request data	            Per-user data across requests